-- 
Thomson Reuters First-Quarter Profit Rises on Legal, Tax Revenue Increases

-- B y   B r e t t   P u l l e y
-- 
2011-04-28T21:23:26Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-28/thomson-reuters-first-quarter-profit-rises-on-legal-tax-revenue-increases.html
Thomson Reuters Corp. (TRI) , the
financial news and information provider, reported first-quarter
profit almost doubled on rising sales of legal, and tax and
accounting products.  Net income advanced to $250 million, or 30 cents a share,
from $127 million, or 15 cents, a year earlier, the New York-
based company said today in a statement. Excluding some items,
profit rose to 42 cents a share from 36 cents. Analysts
projected 43 cents, the average of 14 estimates compiled by
Bloomberg.  Revenue rose 6 percent to $3.33 billion. Analyst on average
estimated $3.23 billion. Sales of legal products advanced
11 percent, while tax and accounting revenue rose 5 percent.  The company also said it plans to sell its enterprise risk
and Portia businesses, with the transactions expected to close
in the second half. Portia provides financial management
software and services. The company said it expects net proceeds
of about $1 billion from the sales of the two businesses.  Thomson Reuters  fell C$1.02, or 2.6 percent, to C$38.11 at
4 p.m. in Toronto Stock Exchange trading. The shares have
advanced 2.3 percent this year.  Bloomberg LP, the parent of Bloomberg News, competes with
Thomson Reuters in selling financial and legal information and
trading systems.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Brett Pulley in New York at 
 bpulley@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
